Dealing with Excel

Carl Frederick

21 September 2018

Working with others = Working with Excel

Agenda

  1. Review a list of R packages that interact with Excel

  2. Focus on strategies for working with spreadsheets that are optimized for human readability instead of machine readability.

Goal

You will remember there is a way to do this in R and this presentation can be a reference/recipe when you need it.

R packages that interact with Excel

The R-Data Import/Export Manual has a “chapter” about interacting with Excel.

“The first piece of advice is to avoid doing so if possible!”

Instead, they suggest opening the spreadsheet, saving as a .csv or similar, and then reading in the .csv file.

Undeterred, I searched CRAN for excel and these are the packages that popped up:

Package Name Reads Writes Notes
My Go-To Packages
openxlsx ✅ ✅ Full function, without Java dependency.
readxl ✅ Lightweight, best for straightforward inputs.
tidyxl ✅ Designed to import human-optimized sheets.
Others I’ve Used
XLConnect ✅ ✅ This one can even do graphics (Java dependency).
xlsx ✅ ✅ Heavy duty, can even format worksheets … everything but graphics (Java dependency).
Haven’t Used
dataframes2xls ✅
excel.link ✅ ✅ Can write .xslb and password protected files.
tatoo ✅ For Excel reports from R with metadata.
writexl ✅ Appears to be complement to readxl
WriteXLS ✅

Import from Excel: Machine Friendly Files

Machine friendly files with variables in columns and observations in rows. Ideally, they have variable names in the top row.

e.g. 2016-17 District Accountability Report Cards

#Download the file
tdir <- tempdir()
fname <- file.path(tdir, "ReportCard_Dist_1617.xlsx")
curl::curl_download(url = "http://dpi.wi.gov/sites/default/files/imce/accountability/xls/2016-17_district_reportcard_data.xlsx", 
              destfile = fname)

Quick look at 2016-17_district_reportcard_data.xlsx

Basic Import: readxl

#Using readxl
library(readxl)

#Check Sheet Names
excel_sheets(fname)
## [1] "Disclaimer"        "About the Data"    "Field Description"

readxl vs openxlsx

readxl openxlsx Notes
Returns (object type) tibble data.frame
Arguments in Common
Skip rows at the top skip startRow Both automatically skip empty rows at top.
Treat 1st row as column names col_names colNames With readxl you can also specify new column names.
Strings to interpret as NAs’ na na.strings Both treat blank cells as NA’s
Arguments that do similar things
Specify rows and/or columns to import range, nmax rows, cols
Tell R the variable types col_types detectDates readxl offers wider range of variable types
Unique to readxl
# values to read to guess column type guess_max ❌
Delete leading/trailing whitespace trim_ws ❌
Unique to openxlsx
Treat 1st column as row names ❌ rowNames
Skip empty rows in middle of data ❌ skipEmptyRows
Skip empty columns in middle of data ❌ skipEmptyCols
Ensure column names are valid R names ❌ check.names
Import only a named region in .xlsx ❌ namedRegion
How to import merged cells ❌ fillMergedCells

Create a useable data.frame

Now that we have the basics down, we can assemble a data.frame and be sure that everything worked correctly.

#Assemble the pieces
subgrp1 <- yrbs17 %>% 
  filter(row == 3) %>% 
  select(col, subgrp1 = character)

#Merged cells are tricky currently
subgrp1 <- bind_rows(
  subgrp1,
  mutate(subgrp1, col = col + 1),
  mutate(subgrp1, col = col + 2)
)
  
subgrp2 <- yrbs17 %>% 
  filter(col == 2, row > 1) %>% 
  select(row, subgrp2 = character)

metric_names <- yrbs17 %>% 
  filter(row == 4) %>% 
  mutate(
    metric_name = case_when(
      character == "Percentage" ~ "pct",
      character == "95% confidence interval" ~ "ci95",
      character == "N" ~ "denominator"
    )
  ) %>% 
  select(col, metric_name)

#In this I have to take that numeric and string contents end up in one column
metrics <- yrbs17 %>% 
  filter(col %in% 3:13, row > 4, row != 16) %>%   
  select(address, row, col, numeric, character) %>% 
  mutate(
    value = if_else(is.na(numeric), character, as.character(numeric))
  ) %>% 
  select(-numeric, -character)

#Start merging to create a single usable data.frame
out <- metrics %>% 
  left_join(metric_names) %>% 
  left_join(subgrp1) %>% 
  left_join(subgrp2) %>% 
  select(subgrp1, subgrp2, metric_name, value) %>%
  spread(metric_name, value)
## Joining, by = "col"
## Joining, by = "col"
## Joining, by = "row"
out %>% 
  select(subgrp1, subgrp2, denominator, pct, ci95) %>% 
  arrange(desc(subgrp1), subgrp2) %>% 
  knitr::kable(.) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling(c("striped", "condensed"), full_width = FALSE)

Writing .xlsx files from R

openxlsx example for one, then many sheets per file

Other packages related to Excel

  • Packages with convenience functions related to Excel
    • rio package for general data import/export across formats, includes wrappers for readxl and openxlsx functions
    • xlsimple wrappers for use with XLConnect
    • table1xls wrappers for use with XLConnect to make summary tables common to scientific articles
    • xltabr wrappers for openxlsx that write “beautifully formatted cross-tabulations” to Excel
    • joinXL uses readxl and openxlsx to perform SQL like joins on Excel files
    • tablaxlsx wrappers to write formatted tables to Excel
  • Non-Excel focused packages that import from Excel
    • datapasta copy-paste data from Excel into an R data.frame
  • Non-Excel focused packages that export to Excel
    • basictabler constructs rich tables for output to html or Excel
    • pivottabler create basic or complex pivot tables in R with output to Excel
    • pdftables converts tables in pdf documents, .xlsx is one of the possible formats
  • BERT is kind of the opposite of the focus of this presentation … it is a designed to
    • support running R functions from Excel spreadsheet cells
    • control Excel in real time from your R code

Have non-Excel spreadsheets?

There are also packages that interact with:

  • Google Sheets: googlesheets
  • ODS (open document spreadsheets): readODS
